{
  "texts": [
    "Euclidean distance is the most common metric for measuring the straight-line distance between two points (or vectors) in a multi-dimensional space.",
    "It calculates the \"as-the-crow-flies\" distance between two vectors, treating each dimension as an axis in a Cartesian plane.",
    "Euclidean distance is widely used in geometric tasks or where the actual distance between points matters.",
    "Manhattan distance, also known as L1 distance or taxicab distance, measures the sum of the absolute differences between the corresponding coordinates of two vectors.",
    "Instead of measuring the direct straight-line distance (as in Euclidean), Manhattan distance measures how far one would have to travel along the axes of the space."
  ]
}